  "prompt": "Can you travel at the speed of light?",
  "response": "According to our current understanding of physics, based on Albert Einstein's theory of relativity, traveling at the speed of light is not possible for objects with mass. As an object with mass accelerates closer to the speed of light, its relativistic mass increases, requiring an infinite amount of energy to reach the speed of light itself. This makes it impossible for anything with mass to travel at light speed.\n\nLight, on the other hand, consists of massless particles called photons, which naturally travel at the speed of light. In theoretical physics, certain hypothetical particles such as tachyons are proposed to move faster than light, but they remain speculative and are not supported by experimental evidence.\n\nOverall, the speed of light remains a fundamental constant and a cosmic speed limit in our current understanding of the universe.",
